Our Services
Job Site Inspections
The Construction General Permit requires all construction activity to be monitored per Risk Level. Greater Bay Area Environmental will perform construction site inspections of BMP's once per week, In the event of a Qualifying Rain Event, Greater Bay Area Environmental will perform construction site inspections 48 hours prior to, during, and not later than 48 hours after the event. Greater Bay Area Environmental will also inspect the site quarterly for authorized and unauthorized discharges. Samples may also be required, depending on the Risk Level of the job; per the Construction General Permit.Greater Bay Area Environmental will communicate the status of our findings to the responsible staff member(s) to ensure that the Storm Water Pollution Prevention Program is understood and in compliance per the Construction General Permit.Weather Monitoring:Greater Bay Area Environmental will provide weather forecast monitoring and rain event information at the time of the SWPPP inspection.Per Construction General Permit regulations, a weather gauge is required on site.
Sampling and Analysis
Greater Bay Area Environmental will perform all storm water sampling and analysis requirements. Greater Bay Area Environmental will arrive on the construction site, take the required samples, and have them analyzed. Results usually take one to three days depending on the constituent:•      pH•      TurbidityIn the event of a non-storm water discharge, sampling will be necessary to determine the extent of contamination. A suite of constituents will be sampled if suspected non-visible pollutants are discharging. The constituents are posted below:•      Oil & Grease•      Total Dissolved Solids•      Nitrate•      pH•      BOD (Biological Oxygen Demand)
Annual Report for Storm Water Discharges & Notice of Termination (NOT) Filing
Storm Water Multi-Application Reporting and Tracking System (SMARTS) allows an individual builder discharger to file and submit their Annual Report electronically to the Regional Water Board. Greater Bay Area Environmental specialists will help clients complete these tasks successfully.An annual report is required to be submitted to your local Regional Water Quality Control Board by September 1 of each year. This document must be certified and signed, under penalty of perjury, by the appropriate official of your company. Many of the Annual Report questions require an explanation. Greater Bay Area Environmental will provide explanations on a separate sheet as an attachment. We strongly recommend you retain a copy of the completed Annual Report for your records. The SWPPP permit changes went into effective July 2010, and require builders at construction jobsites of more than one acre who disturb soil, to be compliant on their jobsites throughout the year,especially during the rainy season (October 1st - May 1st), with the following:•    Rainfall Erosivity Waiver- Self certifying Erosivity value for smaller construction sites.•    Numeric action Levels- (NALs) for PH and Turbidity.•    Numeric Effluent Levels- (NELs) for PH and Turbidity.•    Risk Based Permitting - 3 levels determined by project sediment risk and receiving water risk.•    Minimum Requirements- Imposes more minimum BMP requirements (see manual).•    Project soil monitoring and reporting- Optional monitoring to provide better risk determination.•    Effluent Monitoring and Reporting -required for PH and Turbidity in stormwater discharges.•    Receiving Water Monitoring and Reporting - Requires some Risk 3 discharges to monitorreceiving waters and conduct bio assessments.•    Post-Construction Standards - Specifies run-off reduction requirements for all sites notcovered by a Phase I or Phase II NPDES MS4 permit.•    Rain Event Action Plan (REAP) - Sites must develop a REAP to protect all exposed portionsof the site within 48 hours prior to a rain event.•    Annual Reporting - All sites enrolled for more than one continuous three-month period to submit information and annually certify that their site is in compliance.



